        <mxCell id="ttZCbK3ra_AwcMFaCHn2-194" parent="1" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;align=center;verticalAlign=middle;rounded=0;" value="&lt;b style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;font style=&quot;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;Hypothesis Tests Summary&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="30" width="300" x="20" y="20" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="ttZCbK3ra_AwcMFaCHn2-196" parent="1" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rounded=1;strokeColor=none;strokeWidth=0.5;" value="&lt;div style=&quot;line-height: 100%;&quot;&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; margin-top: 0px; line-height: 100%;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 14px;&quot;&gt;&lt;b style=&quot;&quot;&gt;CENTRAL LIMIT THEOREM (CLT)&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: light-dark(rgb(0, 0, 0), rgb(255, 255, 255)); box-sizing: inherit;&quot;&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;ng-star-inserted&quot; style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(26, 28, 30); font-family: Inter, sans-serif; animation: auto ease 0s 1 normal none running none !important; transition: none !important;&quot;&gt;If you have enough data (usually n &amp;gt; 30), the&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;ng-star-inserted&quot; style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(26, 28, 30); font-family: Inter, sans-serif; animation: auto ease 0s 1 normal none running none !important; transition: none !important;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;ng-star-inserted&quot; style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; animation: auto ease 0s 1 normal none running none !important; transition: none !important;&quot;&gt;average&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;ng-star-inserted&quot; style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(26, 28, 30); font-family: Inter, sans-serif; animation: auto ease 0s 1 normal none running none !important; transition: none !important;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;of your data will behave like a Bell Curve, even if the raw data itself does not.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;blockquote style=&quot;margin: 0 0 0 40px; border: none; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;line-height: 100%;&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;line-height: 100%;&quot;&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;box-sizing: inherit; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-family: Inter, sans-serif;&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="75" width="340" x="20" y="820" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="ttZCbK3ra_AwcMFaCHn2-204" parent="1" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;rounded=1;strokeWidth=0.5;" value="&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;font style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;font style=&quot;font-size: 14px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(26, 28, 30); font-family: Inter, sans-serif;&quot;&gt;&lt;b style=&quot;&quot;&gt;P-value&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: light-dark(#ffffff, var(--ge-dark-color, #121212));&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(26, 28, 30); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;ng-star-inserted&quot; style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; background-color: light-dark(#ffffff, var(--ge-dark-color, #121212)); animation: auto ease 0s 1 normal none running none !important; transition: none !important;&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#1a1c1e&quot; face=&quot;Inter, sans-serif&quot; style=&quot;font-size: 9px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;&quot;&gt;P-values in Comparison tests and in Regression/Correlation measure the probability of the Null Hypothesis, but because the Null Hypothesis changes, they should be interpreted in two different ways.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;b&gt;P-value in Comparison Tests (e.g., T-test):&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;&quot;&gt;They measure how much &quot;overlap&quot; exists between the distributions of the groups. The default Null Hypothesis is that the groups are the same. Therefore:&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;P-value ≈ 0: Means the distributions represent two distinct populations (little to no overlap). This is statistically significant; the difference observed is likely real and not due to random chance.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;P-value ≈ 1: Means the distributions are nearly 100% overlapping (identical). This is not statistically significant; any difference between them is purely random.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="170" width="420" x="1230" y="560" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="ttZCbK3ra_AwcMFaCHn2-207" parent="1" style="shape=image;verticalLabelPosition=bottom;labelBackgroundColor=default;verticalAlign=top;aspect=fixed;imageAspect=0;image=data:image/png,;" value="" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="133.48" width="311.83" x="1279.08" y="723" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="ttZCbK3ra_AwcMFaCHn2-208" parent="1" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;rounded=1;strokeWidth=0.5;" value="&lt;div style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;b style=&quot;color: light-dark(rgb(26, 28, 30), rgb(212, 214, 216)); font-size: 9px; font-family: Inter, sans-serif; background-color: light-dark(#ffffff, var(--ge-dark-color, #121212));&quot;&gt;P-value in Regression and Correlation Tests:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(26, 28, 30); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;ng-star-inserted&quot; style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; background-color: light-dark(#ffffff, var(--ge-dark-color, #121212)); animation: auto ease 0s 1 normal none running none !important; transition: none !important;&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#1a1c1e&quot; face=&quot;Inter, sans-serif&quot; style=&quot;font-size: 9px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;&quot;&gt;They aim to check if a specific predictor (X) has an impact on the outcome (Y), represented by the slope of the line in a scatter plot. The Null Hypothesis assumes the samples are unrelated (Slope = 0). Therefore:&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;P-value ≈ 0: Means the samples are related. It confirms the slope is significantly different from zero. (Note: The slope does not have to be 1; it just has to be a real, non-zero angle).&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;P-value ≈ 1: Means the samples are unrelated. The slope of the best-fit line is 0 (a flat horizontal line), meaning Y remains constant independently of X.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;&quot;&gt;While the P-value tells us if a relationship exists, it does not tell us how strong it is. For that, we must look at:&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;R squared (0 to 1): How well the line fits the data (Predictive Power).&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Pearson&#39;s r (-1 to 1): The strength and direction of the correlation.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="170" width="420" x="1230" y="850" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="ttZCbK3ra_AwcMFaCHn2-210" parent="1" style="shape=image;verticalLabelPosition=bottom;labelBackgroundColor=default;verticalAlign=top;aspect=fixed;imageAspect=0;image=data:image/png,;" value="" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="130" width="317.03" x="1279.08" y="1020" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="7nWFPXopERBmQTWbtrVL-1" parent="1" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;align=center;verticalAlign=middle;rounded=0;" value="&lt;font style=&quot;font-size: 14px;&quot;&gt;&lt;b style=&quot;&quot;&gt;MANOVA&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: x-small;&quot;&gt;after a MANOVA test we split into ANOVA tests by Bonferroni. After this, it follows the normal Post-hoc test that ANOVAs follow.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="50" width="150" x="1250" y="405.85" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
